<!-- Thank you for submitting a pull request! Find more information 
at https://trino.io/development/process.html, 
at https://github.com/trinodb/trino/blob/master/.github/DEVELOPMENT.md 
and contact us on #core-dev in Slack. -->
<!-- Provide an overview for maintainers and reviewers. -->
## Description
Utilize flathash for iceberg equality deletes to reduce memory usage.
@dain suggested using flathash here: https://github.com/trinodb/trino/pull/21441#discussion_r1613967243

For workloads with many equality deletes, worker was OOM when loading all equality deletes into memory. Flathash reduces memory usage drastically and as a bonus the vectorized execution also appears to reduce wall clock time.

See `testLargeScaleUpsertWorkload` test for example workload of large numbers of equality deletes.
(before)
<img width="1256" height="265" alt="Screenshot 2026-05-27 at 10 02 40 AM" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d3ffd294-ac93-4697-a7d1-163324878574" />

(after)
[
<img width="1257" height="274" alt="Screenshot 2026-05-27 at 10 02 30 AM" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3479824c-62cd-43f2-81cd-bc561bd0ae80" />
](url)
Risks:
- Due to FlatHash not being thread safe, it is guarded with a readwritelock. There is some risk of contention on the lock if many concurrent equality deletes are all read and inserted into the FlatHash at the same time. This is probably not a problem in practice given equality delete loading is IO bound for norma

